<paragraph id="EA0D8115DF23FFDA97AEEC07FDFE9B4C" blockId="2.[136,556,532,559]" box="[136,556,532,559]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
<heading id="B1453679DF23FFDA97AEEC07FDFE9B4C" box="[136,556,532,559]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" reason="3">
<treatmentCitationGroup id="CAA2A63BDF23FFDA97AEEC07FDFE9B4C" box="[136,556,532,559]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
<treatmentCitation id="6B13A704DF23FFDA97AEEC07FDFE9B4C" author="Aiton, W." box="[136,556,532,559]" page=")" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" year="1789">
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA97AEEC07FDFE9B4C" authority="Aiton (1789: 394)" authorityName="Aiton" authorityPageNumber="394" authorityYear="1789" box="[136,556,532,559]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Notoceras" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bicorne">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA97AEEC07FE899B4D" bold="true" box="[136,347,532,559]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Notoceras bicorne</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA9644EC07FDFE9B4C" author="Aiton, W." box="[354,556,532,558]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref3211" refString="Aiton, W. (1789) Hortus kewensis, or, a catalogue of the plants cultivated in the Royal Botanic Garden at Kew by William Aiton Gardener to his Majesty. Vols. 1 - 2. George Nicol, London. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 116053" type="book" year="1789">Aiton (1789: 394)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</treatmentCitation>
</treatmentCitationGroup>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EA0D8115DF23FFDA97AEEC4FFA549D9C" blockId="2.[136,1452,603,2071]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
Aiton’s protologue (1789: 394) of 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA9531EC4EFD3A9B14" authorityName="Aiton" authorityYear="1789" box="[535,744,604,630]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Erysimum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bicorne">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9531EC4EFD3A9B14" box="[535,744,604,630]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Erysimum bicorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consisted of a short diagnosis (“6. E. [
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA938FEC48FAF69B14" box="[1193,1316,603,630]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Erysimum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Erysimum</taxonomicName>
] lanceolatis pilosis, siliquis apice bicornibus”) followed by six annotations: 1) “Horned Hedge-mustard”; 2) “ 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA93FFEC92FAD39BF8" authorityName="Slipinski" authorityYear="2007" box="[1241,1281,641,666]" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Nat" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA93FFEC92FAD39BF8" box="[1241,1281,641,666]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Nat</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. of the Canary Islands. Mr. 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA963CECB6FE039BDC" box="[282,465,677,702]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Francis Masson</emphasis>
.”; 3) “ 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9502ECB7FDA39BDC" box="[548,625,676,702]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Introd.</emphasis>
1779”; 4) “ 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA95DBECB7FCC49BDC" box="[765,790,676,702]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fl</emphasis>
. August and September”; 5) “G. H.” [indicating that this species is cultivated in the Green House at Kew (see 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA95F4ECDBFC899B80" author="Aiton, W." box="[722,859,712,738]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref3211" refString="Aiton, W. (1789) Hortus kewensis, or, a catalogue of the plants cultivated in the Royal Botanic Garden at Kew by William Aiton Gardener to his Majesty. Vols. 1 - 2. George Nicol, London. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 116053" type="book" year="1789">Aiton, 1789</bibRefCitation>
: page xxx, abreviations)]; and 6) “ʘ” [indicating that this species is annual [ʘ] (see 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA96F8ECFFFDBA9A64" author="Aiton, W." box="[478,616,748,774]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref3211" refString="Aiton, W. (1789) Hortus kewensis, or, a catalogue of the plants cultivated in the Royal Botanic Garden at Kew by William Aiton Gardener to his Majesty. Vols. 1 - 2. George Nicol, London. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 116053" type="book" year="1789">Aiton, 1789</bibRefCitation>
: page xxx, abreviations)], and a complete description of the plant: “Descr. 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA97AEED03FF029A48" box="[136,208,784,810]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
<collectingCountry id="92A5C185DF23FFDA97AEED03FF029A48" box="[136,208,784,810]" name="Indonesia" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Flores</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
parvi, flavi. 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA9644ED03FE719A48" box="[354,419,784,810]" class="Demospongiae" family="Phloeodictyidae" genus="Calyx" kingdom="Animalia" order="Haplosclerida" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9644ED03FE719A48" box="[354,419,784,810]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Calyx</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
flavescens, extus pilosus. 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA95E9ED03FCF99A48" box="[719,811,784,810]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Siliquae</emphasis>
approximatae, adpressae, ex ancipiti tetragonae, pilosae, tri-vel quadrilineares, apice bicornes. 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA9509ED27FDA09A2C" box="[559,626,820,846]" class="Nemertea (awaiting allocation)" family="Nemertea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Stylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nemertea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Nemertea" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9509ED27FDA09A2C" box="[559,626,820,846]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Stylus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
persistens, capillaris, longitudine cornuum. 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9344ED27FB629A2C" box="[1122,1200,820,846]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Stigma</emphasis>
capitatum, integrum”. William Aiton set to work in the 1780s to catalogue every plant being grown at Kew. The result, published in 1789, was called 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA97F4ED6EFE599AF4" box="[210,395,892,918]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Hortus kewensis</emphasis>
and included information on the country of origin of every plant, and who first cultivated it in Britain. The botanical descriptions in the 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA957AEDB2FCC79AD8" box="[604,789,928,954]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Hortus kewensis</emphasis>
were not made by the Aitons (William Aiton [1731–1793] and William Townsend Aiton [1766–1849]), but by Daniel Carl Solander, Jonas Carlsson Dryander and Robert Brown, based on material from Kew. On the other hand, some of the new taxa described in the first edition of the 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9278EDFAFF3E9D44" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Hortus kewensis</emphasis>
, published in 1789, originated from L’Héritier (so indicated) and the 
<typeStatus id="35093FB7DF23FFDA94D3EA1EFBE29D45" box="[1013,1072,1037,1063]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">types</typeStatus>
of those taxa are in the L’Héritier herbarium at G-DC. Concretely, as indicated by 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA9593EA23FC859D28" author="Britten, J." box="[693,855,1072,1098]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="1 - 16" refId="ref3431" refString="Britten, J. (1912) The history of Aiton's &quot; Hortus Kewensis &quot;. Journal of Botany 50 (Suppl. 3): 1 - 16." type="journal article" year="1912">Britten (1912)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA94B7EA23FBF39D29" author="Krok, T. O. B. N." box="[913,1057,1072,1099]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref3702" refString="Krok, T. O. B. N. (1925) Bibliotheca botanica suecana. Almqvist &amp; Wiksell, Uppsala &amp; Stockholm, 799 pp." type="book" year="1925">Krok (1925)</bibRefCitation>
, the diagnoses in 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA93D7EA22FA7E9D28" box="[1265,1452,1072,1098]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Hortus kewensis</emphasis>
vols. 1 &amp; 2 were largely written by Dryander, who used a manuscript left by Solander, and this manuscript is present at the Botany Library at BM. Accordingly, in the Art. 46.8 Ex. 43 of the 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9491EA6BFBB19DF0" box="[951,1123,1144,1170]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Shenzhen Code</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9352EA6BFB719DF0" box="[1140,1187,1144,1170]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">ICN</emphasis>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA9397EA6BFA589DF0" author="Turland, N. J. &amp; Wiersema, J. H. &amp; Barrie, F. R. &amp; Greuter, W. &amp; Hawksworth, D. L. &amp; Herendeen, P. S. &amp; Knapp, S. &amp; Kusber, W. - H. &amp; Li, D. - Z. &amp; Marhold, K. &amp; May, T. W. &amp; McNeill, J. &amp; Monro, A. M. &amp; Prado, J. &amp; Price, M. J. &amp; Smith, G. F." box="[1201,1418,1144,1171]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref4017" refString="Turland, N. J., Wiersema, J. H., Barrie, F. R., Greuter, W., Hawksworth, D. L., Herendeen, P. S., Knapp, S., Kusber, W. - H., Li, D. - Z., Marhold, K., May, T. W., McNeill, J., Monro, A. M., Prado, J., Price, M. J. &amp; Smith, G. F. (Eds.) (2018) International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Shenzhen Code) adopted by the Nineteenth International Botanical Congress Shenzhen, China, July 2017. Regnum Vegetabile 159. Glashutten: Koeltz Botanical Books. https: // doi. org / 10.12705 / Code. 2018" type="book" year="2018">
Turland 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9236EA6AFA909DF0" box="[1296,1346,1144,1170]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
) is indicated “Although the descriptions in Aiton’s 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA95B9EA8EFC859DD4" box="[671,855,1180,1206]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Hortus kewensis</emphasis>
(1789) are generally considered to have been written by Solander or Dryander, the names of new taxa published there are attributed to Aiton, the stated author of the work, except where a name and description were both ascribed in that work to somebody else” (see 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA9386EAF7FAA89D9C" author="Turland, N. J. &amp; Wiersema, J. H. &amp; Barrie, F. R. &amp; Greuter, W. &amp; Hawksworth, D. L. &amp; Herendeen, P. S. &amp; Knapp, S. &amp; Kusber, W. - H. &amp; Li, D. - Z. &amp; Marhold, K. &amp; May, T. W. &amp; McNeill, J. &amp; Monro, A. M. &amp; Prado, J. &amp; Price, M. J. &amp; Smith, G. F." box="[1184,1402,1252,1279]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref4017" refString="Turland, N. J., Wiersema, J. H., Barrie, F. R., Greuter, W., Hawksworth, D. L., Herendeen, P. S., Knapp, S., Kusber, W. - H., Li, D. - Z., Marhold, K., May, T. W., McNeill, J., Monro, A. M., Prado, J., Price, M. J. &amp; Smith, G. F. (Eds.) (2018) International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Shenzhen Code) adopted by the Nineteenth International Botanical Congress Shenzhen, China, July 2017. Regnum Vegetabile 159. Glashutten: Koeltz Botanical Books. https: // doi. org / 10.12705 / Code. 2018" type="book" year="2018">
Turland 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA93D8EAF6FAFD9D9C" box="[1278,1327,1252,1278]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2018
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A2A8D29EDF23FFDA979BEB1BFB799175" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" type="description">
<paragraph id="EA0D8115DF23FFDA979BEB1BFD0F9CEC" blockId="2.[136,1452,603,2071]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
Concretely, 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA966EEB1AFDC89C40" authorityName="Aiton" authorityYear="1789" box="[328,538,1288,1314]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Erysimum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bicorne">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA966EEB1AFDC89C40" box="[328,538,1288,1314]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Erysimum bicorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was offered to the Kew Gardens by Francis Masson, it was brought from the 
<collectingRegion id="28764FF7DF23FFDA97AEEB3FFEE39C24" box="[136,305,1324,1350]" country="Spain" name="Canarias" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Canary Islands</collectingRegion>
in 1778. Francis Masson (1741–1805) was a British plant collector and gardener at Kew. 1760s he travelled to London where he got a gardening job at Kew which was the directed by Sir Joseph Banks, i.e., as plant collector for Kew and working for Banks (
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA9543EB67FD039CEC" author="Fry, C." box="[613,721,1396,1422]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref3489" refString="Fry, C. (2013) The plant hunters: the adventures of the world's greatest botanical explorers. University of Chicago Press &amp; Kew, Chicago and London, 63 pp." type="book" year="2013">Fry 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EA0D8115DF23FFDA979BEB8BFCA19F05" blockId="2.[136,1452,603,2071]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
Masson’s living plants went to Kew and his herbarium specimens (mainly) to Banks and now are preserved at BM, and duplicates of Masson’s collections are in several herbaria, e.g., BR, CGE, DBN, HAL, LD, LINN, MO, 
<collectingCountry id="92A5C185DF23FFDA9260EBAEFABF9CB5" box="[1350,1389,1469,1495]" name="Philippines" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">PH</collectingCountry>
, UPS (incl. Thunberg herbarium) (
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA96E2EBF3FCD29C99" author="Stafleu, F. A. &amp; Cowan, R. S." box="[452,768,1504,1531]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref3928" refString="Stafleu, F. A. &amp; Cowan, R. S. (1981) Taxonomic literature. Ed. 2. Vol. 3. Bohn, Scheltema &amp; Holkema, Utrecht, 980 pp." type="book" year="1981">Stafleu &amp; Cowan 1981: 361</bibRefCitation>
). No such specimen of this species from Masson’s collections and collected in Canary Islands, however, is present at K. The Royal Botanic Gardens at Kew had no herbarium in the 18th century. In addition, as indicated by 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA957AE83BFC4F9F21" author="Stafleu, F. A. &amp; Cowan, R. S." box="[604,925,1576,1603]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref3852" refString="Stafleu, F. A. &amp; Cowan, R. S. (1976) Taxonomic literature. Ed. 2. Vol. 1. Bohn, Scheltema &amp; Holkema, Utrecht, 1136 pp." type="book" year="1976">Stafleu &amp; Cowan (1976: 25)</bibRefCitation>
almost all 
<typeStatus id="35093FB7DF23FFDA933CE83AFB879F21" box="[1050,1109,1577,1603]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">types</typeStatus>
of both editions of the 
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9278E83AFF3E9F04" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Hortus kewensis</emphasis>
are in the Banksian herbarium at BM (Banks herbarium).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EA0D8115DF23FFDA979BE863FB799175" blockId="2.[136,1452,603,2071]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
Fortunately, in the herbarium BM there is a relevant specimen of this author collected in Canary Islands in 1778, with barcode BM000583715. The sheet bears a well preserved specimen, four complete plants, with leaves, flowers and fruits, and a handwritten label: “Insula Canaria. Fr. Masson 1778”. The geographical locality “Insula Canaria” and the author “Fr. Masson” agrees with the locality and author given in the protologue. Therefore, this specimen is undoubtedly original material of 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA953FE912FD5D9E78" authorityName="Aiton" authorityYear="1789" box="[537,655,1792,1818]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Erysimum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bicorne">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA953FE912FD5D9E78" box="[537,655,1792,1818]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">E. bicorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and it was used by Aiton for its description. We have not been able to locate any further original material in other herbaria (e.g., BR, CGE, DBN, G, HAL, LD, LINN, MO, 
<collectingCountry id="92A5C185DF23FFDA922AE936FAE19E5D" box="[1292,1331,1829,1855]" name="Philippines" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">PH</collectingCountry>
, UPS) and possibly the specimen at BM is the only original material used by Aiton in the description of 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA93BAE95AFAC19E00" authorityName="Aiton" authorityYear="1789" box="[1180,1299,1864,1890]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Erysimum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bicorne">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA93BAE95AFAC19E00" box="[1180,1299,1864,1890]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">N. bicorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, as we cannot exclude that there were more than 
<specimenCount id="FCB44A9CDF23FFDA95A4E97EFCC99EE4" box="[642,795,1900,1927]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
of this taxon, we consider the specimen as the 
<typeStatus id="35093FB7DF23FFDA9201E97FFA5C9EE4" box="[1319,1422,1900,1926]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">lectotype</typeStatus>
of the name, admitting that the specimen might well be the 
<typeStatus id="35093FB7DF23FFDA942CE983FCBE9EC8" box="[778,876,1936,1962]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">holotype</typeStatus>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA948FE983FB999EC8" author="McNeill, J." box="[937,1099,1936,1962]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="1112 - 1113" refId="ref3762" refString="McNeill, J. (2014) Holotype specimens and type citations: General issues. Taxon 63 (5): 1112 - 1113. https: // doi. org / 10.12705 / 635.7" type="journal article" year="2014">McNeill 2014</bibRefCitation>
). The specimen BM000583715 is well preserved and complete, and represents the traditional concept and current use of the name (see e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA9211E9A7FA759EAC" author="Ball, P. W." box="[1335,1447,1972,1998]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="280 - 281" refId="ref3302" refString="Ball, P. W. (1964) Notoceras R. Br. In: Tutin, T. G., Heywood, V. H., Burges, N. A., Valentine, D. H., Walters, S. M. &amp; Webb, D. A. (Eds.) Flora Europaea, vol. 1. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, pp. 280 - 281." type="book chapter" year="1964">Ball 1964</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA97AEE9CBFE9E9E90" author="Galan Cela, P." box="[136,332,2008,2034]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="95 - 96" refId="ref3523" refString="Galan Cela, P. (1993) Notoceras R. Br. In: Castroviejo, S., Aedo, C., Gomez Campo, C., Lainz, M., Montserrat, P., Morales, R., Munoz Garmendia, F., Nieto Feliner, F. G., Rico, E., Talavera, S. &amp; Villar, L. (Eds.) Flora iberica, vol. 4. CSIC, Madrid, pp. 95 - 96." type="book chapter" year="1993">Galán Cela 1993</bibRefCitation>
). This specimen was indicated as “type” of 
<taxonomicName id="2DB2FA96DF23FFDA9465E9CAFC6E9E90" authorityName="Aiton" authorityYear="1789" box="[835,956,2008,2034]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Erysimum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="bicorne">
<emphasis id="D8C65D07DF23FFDA9465E9CAFC6E9E90" box="[835,956,2008,2034]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">N. bicorne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="8E23FCE4DF23FFDA94CFE9CBFB7B9E90" author="Jafri, S. M. H." box="[1001,1193,2008,2034]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="1 - 308" refId="ref3618" refString="Jafri, S. M. H. (1973) Brassicaceae In: Nasir, E. &amp; Ali, S. I. (Eds.) Flora of West Pakistan, vol. 55. Ferozsons, Karachi, pp. 1 - 308." type="book chapter" year="1973">Jafri (1973: 194)</bibRefCitation>
“Type: Canary Island, Masson (BM) (see http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=5&amp;taxon_id=250063814).
</paragraph>
